label chapter14:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse | Night]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_1 at full_bg

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, urgent strings; a low drum builds beneath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft click of a key, distant thunder]
    "Narration:"
    "You hold the drive between two fingers, its plastic ridges sticky with greenhouse humidity. The city hums below — generators sounding, a boat's horn, a dog barking three blocks away — but up here the world"
    "narrows to the breath between you and the screen. The document is raw: invoices, annotated blueprints, a private timeline that names investors and parcels and the clauses meant to strip oversight. It smells faintly of rain"
    "and solder and the flat metallic tang of adrenaline."
    "Narration:"
    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq stands behind you, elbows on the reclaimed pallet bench, welding goggles pushed up like a halo. His presence is a warm pressure against your back. He does not reach for the drive; he doesn't need to. You both know what comes next."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "You sure about this? Once it's loose, there's no putting it back."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "They've been moving in the dark for months. People deserve light.' (Your voice is steadier than you feel.) 'If this burns bridges, we'll build across the flames."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "And if the flames reach the Flats first?' (He laughs, not joking.) 'You keep putting the town on the line like it's a map you can redraw."

    mara_lin "It's already drawn. We're just making the menu public."
    "Narration:"
    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq exhales, a small, ragged sound. He looks down at his hands — stained, small cuts catching the light — then back at you."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Alright. Then—"
    "Narration:"
    "he reaches, and for a moment you think he'll take the drive"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "—then we'll weather what comes. Together."
    "Narration:"
    "Your thumb presses the drive into the slot. The upload bar crawls like a tideline. Outside, a gust rattles the greenhouse glass; the first fat drops of rain patter cold against the panes. The progress indicator hops, then surges."

    menu:
        "Attach a short personal note to the release — call out the neighborhoods by name":
            "You type three blunt sentences, voice cracking but honest: 'You cannot buy safety by erasing people.' You attach it. The drive hums; you feel the note as a small, hot ember."
        "Keep it strictly factual and anonymous":
            "You leave your signature off the file, the facts glinting cold and surgical. It will be harder to vilify you, but quieter — letting other people roar for you."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues with the upload sent and immediate fallout."
    "Narration:"
    "You hit send. The greenhouse fills with the sound of your heartbeat and the soft metallic chime of the city accepting a new truth. The files propagate — to independent outlets, to Samira's secure channel, to"
    "a handful of investigative reporters with reputations for not blinking. Within minutes your phone begins to shiver across the bench: texts, unknown numbers, a single, terse voice note from Kai, then an incoming call labeled 'Harbor"
    "— LIVE LINE.'"
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A chorus of pings; a rising, collective intake of breath like wind before a storm]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid string ostinato; percussion snaps increase]
    "Narration:"
    "You close the laptop. The decision has left your hands. For a sliver of time you only feel the aftershock: the warmth of the drive, the cool of the brass compass at your throat, and Ibe's hand finding yours, fingers curling like a promise."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Now we brace."

    mara_lin "We do what we always do. Hold the line."
    # [Scene: Municipal Hall | Night]
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_3 at full_bg

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendo into brass and snare; a civic alarm begins a low wail]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Megaphone shouts, camera shutters, a faint, urgent tapping of a municipal phone line]
    "Narration:"
    "When the Hall's live feed cracks on, it is with the voice of a reporter who says the word 'leak' three times as if testing how loudly truth breaks glass. Inside, Samira's face is a ledger"
    "of guilt and resolution; she whispers into the tablet like she is counting names. Eloise's shadow moves across the civic map, small and sudden, and her hands are folded, her jaw a hard line."
    show eloise_varela at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "These allegations are serious. We will cooperate fully with the investigation."
    show samira_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "I couldn't stop it from getting out once it was in the wild. But I will—' (She straightens.) '—I will block fast approvals. I have signatures ready."
    show mara_lin at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Make it count."
    "Narration:"
    "Reporters press forward. Questions become a clamor: Were there kickbacks? Who stood to gain if neighborhoods were vacated? The Hall's digital map zooms into the parcels named in the documents, an ugly constellation of ownership. Within"
    "an hour, the city's ethics council posts a temporary suspension of any decisions tied to the barrier contracts. The phrase 'temporary suspension' smells like bureaucracy and like victory."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A collective exhalation; the city's heartbeat quickens]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High brass—triumphant, taut]

    "Reporter" "Ms. Lin, sources say this could halt the plan indefinitely. Is that the point?"

    mara_lin "It isn't about halting progress.' (You find your voice in the queue of microphones.) 'It's about who progress is for. We will not be collateral."

    samira_chen "There will be hearings. Community oversight panels will be convened. Citizen representatives will have veto power on displacement measures."
    "Narration:"
    "The words arrive heavy, official, and they land like armor on the town. For a moment the world rearranges into something with breathing room. You feel the moral victory as a physical warmth, like sunlight through glass."

    menu:
        "Take the podium and name the people who will represent the Flats":
            "You step up, lists in hand, and your voice is raw but exact. Names ripple through the crowd; people find themselves called into being."
        "Stay off camera — let Samira and the community spokespeople own the narrative":
            "You step back. Samira speaks with the steadiness of someone who has navigated halls of power before. Your anonymity keeps the attention on the policy, not on you."

    # --- merge ---
    "Regardless of choice, public scrutiny bites into the plan's framework and the immediate policy pause stands."
    "Narration:"
    "No matter which path you take, the consequence is the same: public scrutiny bites into the plan's framework. Investigative reporters parse the spreadsheets you've released. Eloise stands in the Hall's glass atrium and looks, for the"
    "first time, undeniably small. There is a moment where you see something like private guilt cross her face — a conscience misstepping into daylight — but she answers questions with trained angles and promises consultation."

    eloise_varela "We want safety for everyone. We will reconvene."
    "Narration:"
    "You leave before the crowd dissolves. Outside, Kai is a bright exclamation at the market entrance, waving a handkerchief and laughing too hard. People hug. Someone slams a drum. The city has shifted; the Hall is a different beast now, its teeth checked."
    # [Scene: Harbor Market | Dawn]
    hide eloise_varela
    hide samira_chen
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A lull in the percussion—hope threaded with a tremor]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The ebb and flow of conversation, a child's cry, an incoming weather alert tone]
    "Narration:"
    "You move through the market like someone bearing two maps: one public, one private. People press you with thanks and with lists of what they need—sandbags, legal aid, food for volunteers. Rosa squeezes your forearm, soil on her nails like a blessing."
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "You did the right thing, niña. The land remembers when someone speaks for it."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "It feels like we've been given a door to push open."
    "Narration:"
    "The weather alert blares loud enough to make the crowed still: a rapid intensifying coastal low, unexpected surge potential, evacuation advisories for low-lying blocks. The council's suspension buys time on policy; it does nothing to stop the tide."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Warnings layer over the celebration; a sense of imminent movement]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Violins return, rising to a violent sweep]
    "Narration:"
    "There is no time for collective exultation. You and the volunteers snap into movement — tarps, anchors, boats — instincts older than the morning. The Flats must be defended; people must be moved to upper floors. You run through motions you've practiced a hundred times, each repetition a small prayer."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Get the pumps! Check the makeshift levees! I'll get the trucks!"

    mara_lin "Secure the nursery first. Rosa's seedlings—' (You point, voice cutting through the chaos.) '—then the elderly on Pescadero."
    "Narration:"
    "Everything accelerates. Salt spray begins to streak the air into a silver haze. The first surge hits the promenade like someone slamming a palm on a table. Wooden walkways flex and moan. A cry goes up"
    "from the Drowned Promenade — the old lighthouse's lower steps are already slick with seawater. Volunteers shout coordinates; a boat ramps. You feel the push of water through your boots, cold and immediate."
    # [Scene: Drowned Promenade / Old Lighthouse | Storm]
    hide rosa_alvarez
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_7 at full_bg

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive, frenetic; everything percussion and high, wounded strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The ocean's roar, shouted commands, the sickening creak of timber]
    "Narration:"
    "The storm does not respect timing. It arrives sharp and merciless. You follow a path of galvanic decision — a child stuck on a submerged step, a generator sputtering, a makeshift dyke giving way — and"
    "you move like breath: focused, without hesitation. Your gloves are sodden; your hair plastered to your neck. A rope slices your palm; another volunteer calls your name as a board snaps underfoot. Each near-miss lands like"
    "a punctuation mark."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Mara! Get everyone up! I'll—"
    "Narration:"
    "He cuts off as water surges the engine bay."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Ibe—"
    "Narration:"
    "He does not take your hand. He frees the truck, then looks at the line of families, the toddlers clinging to damp blankets, the elder with a cane whose breath fogs like a small, stubborn moon."
    "For an instant something passes between you — something raw and clean: the shape of what you asked for when you released the files. Then he steps toward the truck and the sound of it starting"
    "is like a small, terrible choice."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "I have to get my sister off the Quay. She can't climb that second stair."

    mara_lin "We move together."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "No.' (He shakes his head once, sharp.) 'You gave this thing to the world, Mara. You exposed it. That bought people time — and you know that. But... some of the cost is going to be immediate. I have a choice to make for my blood."
    "Narration:"
    "He is not accusing. He is explaining the wall he erects—not from malice but from survival. He moves with purpose to the truck, fastening straps, barking orders to a neighbor he knows, to a face in"
    "the crowd. You watch him fold his hands around the steering wheel, the talisman a blur in his palm, and then he is driving away, headlights swallowed by rain."

    mara_lin "Ibe, come with us. We can make that a triage route. We can—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "You think this is only about policy?' (He glances back once.) 'Do you think I haven't thought about what happens when the Hall's suspension turns into months? Do you think I don't fear being the person who loses everything while speeches get made?"

    mara_lin "It's never been only about policy.' (You step forward, rain plastering your jacket.) 'But you know what exposing it did. You know the Hall can't proceed blind now."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "And you know what the leak made people believe: that the future could be altered by a fever. Maybe that's true. Maybe it saves lives. Maybe it burns bridges we need.' (He looks at you with a kind of grief.) 'But right now, someone in my family needs me to choose safety over... over the ideal."

    mara_lin "Is protecting your family a betrayal of the rest of us?"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "It's a choice. Like yours.' (He rubs the talisman, and for a second the boy who survived the drought flashes through his jaw.) 'I can't watch people I love get left on a ledger that might be fixed later."
    "Narration:"
    "He does not say he will leave town forever. He does not have to. The truck's taillights vanish into the rain. Somewhere in the chaos, a shout rises: someone rescued, someone lost. The storm churns both redemption and ruin."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Peak; then a single, high sostenuto note that fractures into silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant bell, the low keening of a siren folding into the wind]
    "Narration:"
    "When the water recedes it leaves a new city carved in salt and mud. The Flats have lost a row: a childhood block you counted as permanent now shows the teeth of the sea. Personal artifacts"
    "— a child's painted boat, a tin lunchbox — float like confessions. You wade through the aftermath with hands that will not stop moving. Volunteers chant names and patch what can be patched. Samira organizes shelter"
    "and legal contingency in equal measure; Rosa comforts a family whose home is hollowed out to the studs."
    show rosa_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "We keep planting. Every scar is a ledger of what we defend."
    "Narration:"
    "The investigations continue. Eloise stands before a council with her plan stripped for public audit; the city requires community oversight panels and funds are redirected to hybrid, community-centered solutions. The civic map fills in new colors:"
    "green for restoration pilots, orange for shared infrastructure, blue for community land trusts. It is, outwardly, a moral victory — the kind that tastes of salt and honest sweat."
    hide mara_lin
    hide rosa_alvarez

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fanfare twin with minor key — triumph laced with loss]
    "Narration:"
    "But victory does not stitch every rift. In the hours after, you return to the greenhouse and find the space feeling too small, too intimate for the roof you now carry. The seedlings are battered; you"
    "cup their leaves and feel the grit of what was lost. Your hands shake from work and from the hollowness Ibe left behind."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Did we do the right thing?"
    show rosa_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "You did what you could. The rest is for the living to bear."
    "Narration:"
    "You want to call Ibe. You open your phone and stare at his name — the call icon like an unanswered invitation. You have built a rampart around the town that may hold; you have forced"
    "power into sunlight. And yet the person who stood beside you for months is now a space in the street, a missing laugh."

    mara_lin "Ibe—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "I had to move my sister to dry ground. The kids were scared. I couldn't—' (He swallows.) 'I couldn't risk both my family and getting stuck in a fight that might take years to win."

    mara_lin "We won, Ibe. The plan is paused. They can't just... steamroll everyone now. Community oversight—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "You made them listen. You forced their hands. You did something I admire."

    mara_lin "Then why—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Because winning for the town doesn't erase the night my brother's well dried up and we left everything. Sometimes safety for one door is leaving another behind.' (He inhales.) 'I have to put my family first. I hope you understand."

    mara_lin "Ibe, don't leave like this.' (Your voice cracks.) 'We can rebuild together. We can—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "I don't know how to be in two fights at once. Maybe I never learned. I have to go.' (A pause, the kind that contains a small ending.) 'Take care, Mara."
    "Narration:"
    "The line goes dead. You sit with the phone in your hand until the greenhouse lamp blooms low and warm around you like a last harbor. Outside, the city rearranges: hearings scheduled, restitution funds allocated, volunteer"
    "schedules posted on loops. News anchors parse the months of documents, journalists point out culpability, Eloise issues a statement promising reform."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle, resolute motif — victory tempered with endurance]
    hide mara_lin
    hide rosa_alvarez

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_10 at full_bg
    "Narration:"
    "You stand up and fasten your compass at your throat. It is not a talisman against grief; it is a tool. You still have plans to make: marshes to replant, legal meetings to sit through, oversight"
    "panels to staff with the people whose names you called out. The town needs you steady. Ibe needs what he needs. The two can no longer occupy the same small space in your life."
    "Narration:"
    "You step into the market. People press your shoulder with quiet thanks. A child pushes a sodden paper boat into your palm. You plant it on a tray of nursery mud in an act that is both literal and metaphorical: something small, fragile, viable."
    "Narration:"
    "Outside the Hall, banners still flap. The city will never be the same — safer in some tangible ways, marked in others by displacement and memory. You have changed the course of a plan that would"
    "have cost lives and culture; that is a truth that steadies you. The fracture with Ibe will ache. It will be a lesson and a loss."
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "Keep coming back, Mara. The town is a long arc."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "I will."
    "Narration:"
    "The moral victory is real, hard-earned, and public. Investigations hum. Council meetings fill with ordinary people with extraordinary stakes. Community-led pilots bloom in odd places: a regraded shoreline, a portable pump program run by locals, a"
    "tiny fund for emergency relocation that is managed by residents, not developers. Those are the wins you wanted when you pressed send."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Resolute, ascending — a final chord that is warm, not blinding]
    hide rosa_alvarez
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_11 at full_bg
    "Narration:"
    "You stand on the quay, the compass warm and pressed against your skin, and let the city breathe around you. There is pain; there is loss; there is also this: that truth in the open air"
    "catalyzed something stronger than the sterile promise of a barrier. For that, you will grieve and work in equal measure. For that, the town will keep its character and, slowly, its dignity."

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_12 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
